{"parse":{"title":"Copybook (education)","pageid":26929187,"revid":828507029,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For another definition of \"copybook\", see <a href=\"/wiki/Exercise_book\" title=\"Exercise book\">Exercise book</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Copy_book,_Boston,_1840-1850,_manuscript_on_paper,_board_-_Concord_Museum_-_Concord,_MA_-_DSC05607.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Copy_book%2C_Boston%2C_1840-1850%2C_manuscript_on_paper%2C_board_-_Concord_Museum_-_Concord%2C_MA_-_DSC05607.JPG/220px-Copy_book%2C_Boston%2C_1840-1850%2C_manuscript_on_paper%2C_board_-_Concord_Museum_-_Concord%2C_MA_-_DSC05607.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"140\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Copy_book%2C_Boston%2C_1840-1850%2C_manuscript_on_paper%2C_board_-_Concord_Museum_-_Concord%2C_MA_-_DSC05607.JPG/330px-Copy_book%2C_Boston%2C_1840-1850%2C_manuscript_on_paper%2C_board_-_Concord_Museum_-_Concord%2C_MA_-_DSC05607.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f9/Copy_book%2C_Boston%2C_1840-1850%2C_manuscript_on_paper%2C_board_-_Concord_Museum_-_Concord%2C_MA_-_DSC05607.JPG/440px-Copy_book%2C_Boston%2C_1840-1850%2C_manuscript_on_paper%2C_board_-_Concord_Museum_-_Concord%2C_MA_-_DSC05607.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"4984\" data-file-height=\"3172\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Copy_book,_Boston,_1840-1850,_manuscript_on_paper,_board_-_Concord_Museum_-_Concord,_MA_-_DSC05607.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Penmanship copybook, Boston, Massachusetts, 1840-1850</div></div></div>\n<table role=\"presentation\" class=\"mbox-small plainlinks sistersitebox\" style=\"background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<td class=\"mbox-image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"40\" class=\"noviewer\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/45px-Commons-logo.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/59px-Commons-logo.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1024\" data-file-height=\"1376\" /></td>\n<td class=\"mbox-text plainlist\">Wikimedia Commons has media related to <i><b><a href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Copybooks\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"commons:Category:Copybooks\">Copybooks</a></b></i>.</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>A <b>copybook</b>, or <b>copy book</b> is a book used in education that contains examples of handwriting and blank space for learners to <a href=\"/wiki/Imitation\" title=\"Imitation\">imitate</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Typical uses include teaching <a href=\"/wiki/Penmanship\" title=\"Penmanship\">penmanship</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Arithmetic\" title=\"Arithmetic\">arithmetic</a> to students.  A page of a copy book typically starts with a copybook heading: a printed example of what should be copied, such as a single <a href=\"/wiki/Letter_(alphabet)\" title=\"Letter (alphabet)\">letter</a> or a short <a href=\"/wiki/Proverb\" title=\"Proverb\">proverb</a>. The rest of the page is empty, except for horizontal rulings. The student is expected to copy the example down the page. By copying, the student is supposed to practise penmanship, <a href=\"/wiki/Spelling\" title=\"Spelling\">spelling</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Reading_comprehension\" title=\"Reading comprehension\">reading comprehension</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Punctuation\" title=\"Punctuation\">punctuation</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Vocabulary\" title=\"Vocabulary\">vocabulary</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Uses\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Uses</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#In_popular_culture\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">In popular culture</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Copybook_(education)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>The American Instructor: Or, Young Man's Best Companion</i>, published in 1748, was the first American copybook.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The 1802 book <i>The Port folio</i> recommends the copybook method of learning fine penmanship over the previously used method of \"engraved models\", citing the advantage of having the example text closer to the student's reproduction. The author adds, \"A neat copybook has often laid the foundation, or shown the first symptoms, of taste in all the elegant arts of life.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Copybooks are still available for purchase today, but unlike older copybooks many modern ones use print and cursive fonts as the writing examples instead of real handwriting.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Uses\">Uses</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Copybook_(education)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Uses\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Because in the 18th century good penmanship was primarily considered an important business skill, the copybooks frequently were oriented towards <a href=\"/wiki/Autodidact\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Autodidact\">autodidacts</a> wishing to learn business skills, and therefore included chapters on general business management as well as lessons in accounting.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Other copybooks, however, focused chiefly on writing literacy and used <a href=\"/wiki/Maxim_(philosophy)\" title=\"Maxim (philosophy)\">maxims</a> and sometimes Bible verses as their material. It was intended that students memorize not only correct penmanship, but correct morals as well, through exposure to traditional sayings.\n</p><p>Copybooks were also published in geography, the student being asked to copy first names onto an unlabelled map, and later whole maps onto a latitude/longitude grid.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>There are also botanical copybooks like <i><a href=\"/wiki/Studies_of_Flowers_from_Nature\" title=\"Studies of Flowers from Nature\">Studies of Flowers from Nature</a></i> that were popular in the 19th century for developing watercolor painting skills. Here the student would paint an image for which the outline was already drawn in (like a modern coloring book), using as a model a finished watercolor provided by the book's illustrator.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"In_popular_culture\">In popular culture</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Copybook_(education)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: In popular culture\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Rudyard_Kipling\" title=\"Rudyard Kipling\">Rudyard Kipling</a> published a poem called <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Gods_of_the_Copybook_Headings\" title=\"The Gods of the Copybook Headings\">The Gods of the Copybook Headings</a></i> in October 1919, a lesson to keep to common sense.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Copybook_(education)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Notebook\" title=\"Notebook\">Notebook</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Exercise_book\" title=\"Exercise book\">Exercise book</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Examination_book\" title=\"Examination book\">Examination book</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Laboratory_notebook\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Laboratory notebook\">Laboratory notebook</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Copybook_(education)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/copybook\">\"Definition of copybook in English\"</a>. Oxford University Press<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">28 March</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Definition+of+copybook+in+English&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fen.oxforddictionaries.com%2Fdefinition%2Fcopybook&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACopybook+%28education%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Tamara Plakins Thornton, \"Handwriting in America: A cultural history.\" Page 12.<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=g5cHxU9EXjkC\">[1]</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=nq4RAAAAYAAJ\">Joseph Dennie, Asbury Dickens, \"The Port folio\", 1802. Page 303</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Tamara Plakins Thornton, \"Handwriting in America: A cultural history.\" Page 12.<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=g5cHxU9EXjkC\">[2]</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Otis, Broaders and Company. American Annals of Education. 1833. Page 382. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=SCuIupZ3pxAC\">https://books.google.com/books?id=SCuIupZ3pxAC</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.lib.cam.ac.uk/deptserv/rarebooks/flowers.html\">\"Featured Book Archive: Miss Smith\"</a>. University of Cambridge Library website.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Copybook_(education)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i>American Penmanship, 1800-1850: A history of writing and a bibliography of copybooks from Jenkins to Spencer</i>. American Antiquarian Society. 1969.</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Copybook_(education)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20090130090150/http://enfsi.eu/page.php?uid=76\">European Network of Forensic Science Institutes - Copybook models and handwriting samples database</a></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.memorialhall.mass.e